```typescript
const countNeighbors = (x: number, y: number, alive: Set<string>): number => {
  let count = 0;
  for (let dx = -1; dx <= 1; dx++) {
    for (let dy = -1; dy <= 1; dy++) {
      if (dx === 0 && dy === 0) continue;
      if (alive.has(`${x + dx},${y + dy}`)) count++;
    }
  }
  return count;
};

export const nextGeneration = (grid: number[][]): number[][] => {
  const alive = new Set(grid.map(([x, y]) => `${x},${y}`));
  return grid.filter(([x, y]) => {
    const neighbors = countNeighbors(x, y, alive);
    return neighbors === 2 || neighbors === 3;
  });
};
```

The test (line 20-24):
```typescript
it("should bring a dead cell to life when it has exactly 3 live neighbors (reproduction)", () => {
    const cells = [[0, 1], [1, 1], [0, 0]];
    const result = nextGeneration(cells);
    expect(result).toEqual(expect.arrayContaining([[1, 0]]));
});
```

Need to add birth/reproduction logic: find dead cells adjacent to living cells and check if they have exactly 3 live neighbors. The countNeighbors helper already exists and can be reused.

